Introducrion

The microbiome R package facilitates exploration and analysis of microbiome profiling data, in particular 16S taxonomic profiling.

This vignette provides a brief overview with example data sets from published microbiome profiling studies (Lahti et al. 2014, Lahti et al. (2013), O’Keefe et al. (2015)). A more comprehensive tutorial is available on-line.

alpha多样性

microbiome极大的扩展了alpha多样性的内容

这里首次（我自己定义的）将alpha分的这么细，随着近年来网络的风靡，和关键微生物类群的文章层出不穷，多样性增加了许多指标。 丰富性，均匀性，多样性，支配性（dominance）和稀有性（rarity）的各种度量。有关参数调整的更多选项，请参见各个功能 注意：这里均是默认的参数运行的全部alpha多样性指标 一共有23中指标; 这里有两种指标包含在phyloseq中，使用 estimate_richness函数计算，所以这里不能计算这两个指标。

beta多样性排序

https://microbiome.github.io/tutorials/Ordination.html

# Convert to compositional data
pseq <- pseq.rel <- microbiome::transform(ps, "compositional")

# Pick core taxa with with the given prevalence and detection limits
pseq.core <- core(pseq.rel, detection = .1/100, prevalence = 90/100)
# Use relative abundances for the core
pseq.core <- microbiome::transform(pseq.core, "compositional")
# Ordinate the data
set.seed(4235421)
# proj <- get_ordination(pseq, "MDS", "bray")
ord <- ordinate(pseq, "MDS", "bray")
plot_ordination(pseq, ord, color = "Group") +
                geom_point(size = 5)

pseq.cca <- ordinate(pseq, "CCA")
p <- plot_ordination(pseq, pseq.cca,
       type = "samples", color = "Group")
p <- p + geom_point(size = 4)
print(p)

# With taxa:
p <- plot_ordination(pseq, pseq.cca,
       type = "taxa", color = "Phylum")
p <- p + geom_point(size = 4)
print(p)

微生物组成展示-核心微生物提取和可视化

提取相对丰度超过0.01的微生物，核心微生物提取和可视化：https://microbiome.github.io/tutorials/Core.html；

core函数用于提取核心微生物群落数据，detection代表提取相对丰度大于某个阈值的微生物。prevalence 代表出现额概率超过百分之多少的样本。

ps_rela =  microbiome::transform(ps, "compositional")
pseq <- ps_rela %>% 
  core(detection = 0.01, prevalence = 50/100)

# With compositional (relative) abundances
det <- c(0, 0.1, 0.5, 2, 5, 20)/100
prevalences <- seq(.05, 1, .05)
 #ggplot(d) + geom_point(aes(x, y)) + scale_x_continuous(trans="log10", limits=c(NA,1))


plot_core(pseq,prevalences = prevalences, detections = det, plot.type = "lineplot") + xlab("Relative Abundance (%)")

p <- pseq %>%
  plot_composition(sample.sort = "Firmicutes", otu.sort = "abundance") 

print(p)

物种共有和特有情况分析可视化

物种存在与否做一个Ven图： https://microbiome.github.io/tutorials/core_venn.html

library(eulerr)
library(microbiome)
# library(microbiomeutilities)
# # install.packages("devtools")
# devtools::install_github("microsud/microbiomeutilities")
pseq.rel <- microbiome::transform(ps, "compositional")
disease_states <- unique(as.character(meta(pseq.rel)$Group))
print(disease_states)
## [1] "KO" "OE" "WT"
list_core <- c() # an empty object to store information

for (n in disease_states){ # for each variable n in DiseaseState
    #print(paste0("Identifying Core Taxa for ", n))
    
    ps.sub <- subset_samples(pseq.rel, Group == n) # Choose sample from DiseaseState by n
    
    core_m <- core_members(ps.sub, # ps.sub is phyloseq selected with only samples from g 
                           detection = 0.001, # 0.001 in atleast 90% samples 
                           prevalence = 0.75)
    print(paste0("No. of core taxa in ", n, " : ", length(core_m))) # print core taxa identified in each DiseaseState.
    list_core[[n]] <- core_m # add to a list core taxa for each group.
    #print(list_core)
}
## [1] "No. of core taxa in KO : 106"
## [1] "No. of core taxa in OE : 107"
## [1] "No. of core taxa in WT : 108"
mycols <- c(nonCRC="#d6e2e9", CRC="#cbf3f0", H="#fcf5c7") 
plot(venn(list_core),
     fills = mycols)

使用DEsep2做差异分析

此为外界端口

https://microbiome.github.io/tutorials/deseq2.html

library(magrittr)



# Only check the core taxa to speed up examples
pseq <- core(ps, detection = 50, prevalence = 80/100)

library(phyloseq)
library(reshape2)
library(DESeq2)
library(knitr)

# Running the DESeq2 analysis
ds2 <- phyloseq_to_deseq2(pseq, ~ Group)
dds <- DESeq(ds2)
res <- results(dds)
df <- as.data.frame(res)
df$taxon <- rownames(df)
df <- df %>% arrange(log2FoldChange, padj)


print(head(kable((df))))
## [1] "|        |   baseMean| log2FoldChange|     lfcSE|       stat|    pvalue|      padj|taxon   |"
## [2] "|:-------|----------:|--------------:|---------:|----------:|---------:|---------:|:-------|"
## [3] "|ASV_41  |  142.64608|     -1.1650662| 0.2489012| -4.6808383| 0.0000029| 0.0000486|ASV_41  |"
## [4] "|ASV_24  |  188.57611|     -1.0859586| 0.2946964| -3.6850076| 0.0002287| 0.0017279|ASV_24  |"
## [5] "|ASV_54  |  116.15914|     -1.0279530| 0.3758856| -2.7347499| 0.0062428| 0.0288902|ASV_54  |"
## [6] "|ASV_6   |  579.78849|     -0.9162078| 0.1609853| -5.6912532| 0.0000000| 0.0000009|ASV_6   |"
# Identify top taxa based on standard ANOVA
source(system.file("extdata/check_anova.R", package = "microbiome"))
ano <- check_anova(pseq, "Group");
ano$log2FC <- log2(ano$ave.KO) - log2(ano$ave.OE)
taxa.anova <- as.character(subset(ano, padj < 0.01 & abs(log2FC) > log2(2))$taxa)

# lowPick the top taxa based on DESEq2
taxa.deseq <- subset(res, padj < 0.01 & abs(log2FoldChange) > log2(2))$taxon

# Check overlap
# Most DESEq2 taxa are confirmed with ANOVA


# Also the est p-values are well correlated (higher not so)
mf <- data.frame(df$padj, ano$padj)
p <- ggplot(mf, aes(x = log10(df$padj), y = log10(ano$padj))) +
  labs(x = 'DESeq2 adjusted p-value', y = 'ANOVA adjusted p-value') +
  geom_point()
print(p)

limma 和t检验

外界端口

https://microbiome.github.io/tutorials/limma.html

# Load libraries
library(microbiome)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)


map = sample_data(ps)
map$ID = row.names(map)
sample_data(ps) = map

pssub =  subset_samples(ps,!Group %in% c("OE"));pssub 
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 2861 taxa and 12 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 12 samples by 12 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 2861 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 2861 tips and 2860 internal nodes ]
otu <- abundances(microbiome::transform(pssub, "log10"))
meta <- meta(pssub)

# Compare the two groups with limma
library(limma)

# Prepare the design matrix which states the groups for each sample
# in the otu
design <- cbind(intercept = 1, Grp2vs1 = meta[["Group"]])
rownames(design) <- rownames(meta)
design <- design[colnames(otu), ]

head(design)
##     intercept Grp2vs1
## KO1         1       1
## KO2         1       1
## KO3         1       1
## KO4         1       1
## KO5         1       1
## KO6         1       1
# NOTE: results and p-values are given for all groupings in the design matrix
# Now focus on the second grouping ie. pairwise comparison
coef.index <- 2

# Fit the limma model
fit <- lmFit(otu, design)
fit <- eBayes(fit)

# Limma P-values
pvalues.limma = fit$p.value[, 2]

# Limma effect sizes
efs.limma <-  fit$coefficients[, "Grp2vs1"]

# Summarise
library(knitr)
kable(topTable(fit, coef = coef.index, p.value=0.1), digits = 2)
logFC AveExpr t P.Value adj.P.Val B
ASV_1908 0.79 0.55 7.04 0 0.01 4.36
ASV_1850 0.74 0.52 6.81 0 0.01 4.02
ASV_204 0.68 1.31 5.76 0 0.02 2.39
ASV_247 0.74 1.12 5.76 0 0.02 2.38
ASV_1909 0.49 0.24 5.76 0 0.02 2.38
ASV_112 0.60 1.50 5.59 0 0.03 2.10
ASV_1191 0.56 0.28 5.40 0 0.03 1.78
ASV_2583 0.55 0.32 5.34 0 0.03 1.67
ASV_1910 0.59 0.43 5.26 0 0.03 1.53
ASV_2076 0.59 0.34 5.25 0 0.03 1.53 
# QQ
qqt(fit$t[, coef.index], df = fit$df.residual + fit$df.prior); abline(0,1)

# Volcano
volcanoplot(fit, coef = coef.index, highlight = coef.index)

# Compare the two groups with t-test
library(dplyr)
pvalues.ttest <- c()
male.samples <- dplyr::filter(meta, Group == "WT")$ID
female.samples <- dplyr::filter(meta, Group == "KO")$ID
for (tax in rownames(otu)) {
  pvalues.ttest[[tax]] <- t.test(otu[tax, male.samples], otu[tax, female.samples])$p.value
}
# Multiple testing correction
pvalues.ttest <- p.adjust(pvalues.ttest, method = "fdr")

# Compare p-values between limma and t-test
taxa <- rownames(otu)
plot(pvalues.ttest[taxa], pvalues.limma[taxa])
abline(0,1,lty = 2)

群落差异检测

外接端口

# Pick relative abundances (compositional) and sample metadata 
pseq.rel <- microbiome::transform(ps, "compositional")
otu <- abundances(pseq.rel)
meta <- meta(pseq.rel)

p <- plot_landscape(pseq.rel, method = "NMDS", distance = "bray", col = "Group", size = 3)
print(p)

# samples x species as input
library(vegan)
permanova <- adonis(t(otu) ~ Group,
                    data = meta, permutations=99, method = "bray")

# P-value
print(as.data.frame(permanova$aov.tab)["Group", "Pr(>F)"])
## [1] 0.01
